This notebook dives into a side project (from my astronomy Ph.D. research) that I wanted to pursue for a couple reasons.  Primarily, I wanted to get more experience with Gaussian process (GP) extrapolation, particularly using the spectral mixture (SM) kernel (explained below).  Additionally, I am interested in a career as a data scientist/analyst in the electric power industry, so it seems natural to apply my Gaussian process experimentation to some form of electric power grid data.  While it is admittedly somewhat backward to approach a data analysis problem with a pre-selected tool in mind, in this case I believe the SM kernel ends up being a useful tool, as the following suggests.

# Gaussian Processes for Electric Load Forecasting

Many services in life that we take for granted require an incredible breadth of behind-the-scene industries and infrastructures to achieve their smooth operation.  The electric power supply--in our homes, offices, stores, and just about everywhere else--is one example.  We only seem to appreciate its availability, reliability, and indispensability when nature disrupts our access, but even then we rarely think beyond the front line utility repairmen.  In actuality, reliable electric service requires a veritable army of workers to generate electric power, oversee its bulk sale and purchase (i.e., electric power markets), operate the power grid, safeguard transmission, and plan and build upgrades (e.g., for enhanced capacity, efficiency, or reliability), to name a few roles.  

In addition to its workforce, a modern power grid also relies on computer algorithms to help plan, operate and monitor the grid and markets.  One specific task that I will explore in this notebook is that of forecasting the electric power demand.  Short-term forecasts (e.g., a few days ahead) in particular are needed to run the day ahead energy market, ensure reliable and economical load distribution, and to support daily generation planning.  Long term forecasts are also important for planning grid expansions and/or modifications and ensuring sufficient future generation capacity, for example.

Forecasters (electric engineers and analysts) often utilize various machine learning algorithms (e.g., neural networks or gaussian proccesses) to produce their predictions.  These models are only as good as the assumptions that go into them, however, so human insights remain an essential, though not overt, ingredient in the forecast.  Many machine learning tools are effectively black boxes that offer little insight into their resulting models (neural networks are especially notorious), so the human interpretation must be gleaned via other means.  Ideally, one would want an interpretable forecasting algorithm that could facilitate transparent detection and correction of the model's failure patterns.  

In this notebook, I want to explore using Gaussian processes (GP) coupled with a particularly powerful spectra mixture (SM) kernel for short-term (24--72 hour) forecasting.  While the ultimate yardstick of prediction is its accuracy, here I am more focused on how to uncover patterns in the historical data that might lead to better predictions, whether with other tools or with more advanced GPs.  To that end, I will show how an SM kernel-based GP can be used to decompose data into periodic and aperiodic components and how this decomposition might be leveraged for enhancing prediction accuracy.

Before diving into forecasting, I will provide a brief, phenomenological overview of Gaussian processes and the SM kernel, as well as set up the Python code needed to facilitate the analysis using GPs.  Next, I will introduce the datasets (electric load, weather) that I intend to use and explore their power spectral densities (for reasons that will be made clear below).  Then I will show some examples of how to decompose the periodic and aperiodic electric load components using the SM kernel.  Finally, I will illustrate how the aperiodic component of the load is strongly dependent on the ambient temperature before discussing other possible applications/refinements of the model.  Be sure to check out the conclusions at the end!

## Gaussian Processes and the Spectral Mixture (SM) Kernel

A simple way to understand a GP is to think of curves sampled from a multivariate normal distribution.  The covariance matrix $\Sigma$ governs the smoothness of these curves and they are always drawn such that every set of sampled points (whether observed or unobserved) has a Gaussian marginal distribution.  The covariance matrix is derived from a kernel function $k(x,x')$ that describes the covariance between every pair of points $x$ and $x'$.  Check out this [tutorial](https://peterroelants.github.io/posts/gaussian-process-tutorial/) and also this [one](http://krasserm.github.io/2018/03/19/gaussian-processes/) for some of the mathematical details regarding Gaussian processes as well as examples showing how to construct them.

Designing a good covariance matrix is the essential challenge in Gaussian process modeling.  Often a covariance matrix based on a single kernel function preforms poorly for interpolation or extrapolation.  It is possible to compose complex kernels through operations on simpler ones, but constructing a composite kernel--which involves having some intuition for what mathematical operations to use and on which sub-kernels to apply them--is a difficult art and not something a machine can readily optimize.

Often, including here, *stationary* kernels are preferred over the more general *non-stationary* ones for their ease of design, interpretation, and computation, despite their reduced flexibility (in general).  A stationary kernel is one where $k(x,x') = k(x-x')$, or for symmetric stationary kernels (the most common case) $k(x,x') = k(|x-x'|)$.  Here, I explore building GPs with a particularly expressive, yet stationary and symmetric kernel function called the spectral mixture (SM) kernel, which was first proposed by [Wilson & Adams (2013)](http://proceedings.mlr.press/v28/wilson13.html).  The authors show that not only is their SM kernel capable of approximating every standard kernel, but its parameters are readily interpretable.  The basic idea is to model the power spectral density of the data using a mixture of Gaussians.  One then obtains the SM kernel by taking the Fourier transform of this mixture.  

Below I coded a Python implementation of the SM kernel.  It is designed to handle either a full matrix of pairwise distances or, using a memory efficient Toeplitz matrix representation, just the first column and/or row of the distance matrix.


```python
import math
import numpy as np

def sm_kernel(pdist, m, v, w, n=None):
    #append an empty axis to `dist` so that it will broadcast to match 
    #Q mixture components (where m, v, and w each have len Q)
    exponent = np.exp(-2 * v * (math.pi * pdist[...,None])**2) 
    cosine = np.cos(2 * math.pi * m * pdist[...,None])
    kernel = np.sum(w * exponent * cosine, axis=-1)
    
    #add extra variance along the diagonal to model for noisy data
    if n is not None:
        if kernel.ndim == 2:   #assume the full kernel matrix is square
            kernel += np.eye(kernel.shape[0]) * n
        elif kernel.ndim == 1:   #kernel is the column/row of a Toeplitz matrix
            kernel[0] += n
    
    return kernel
```

Notice that in real (i.e., not Fourier) space each mixture component is expressed as the product of a Gaussian (squared exponential) and a periodic (cosine) function.  The parameters have a straightforward interpretation.  For each Fourier component, the inverse of the mean frequency gives the period of that component in the kernel and the inverse variance of the Fourier Gaussian is the variance (or squared length scale) of its kernel representation.  Finally, the amplitude of the kernel is the same as its Fourier mixture weight.

The following code segment generates two illustrative SM kernels along with their mixture components.  I have coded the mean and variance parameters as reciprocals to make it easy to understand their values (i.e., the denominators) in frequency space.  Notice that the kernel can consist of both periodic and aperiodic components and even slowly (or quickly) decaying periodic components.


```python
#the covariates, sampled at unit intervals, delta_x = 1 
#so the sampling frequency is also 1 (== 1/delta_x)
x = np.arange(-100,100)

#make up some parameters that will show off the SM kernel
pars1 = np.array([(1/100, 1/40, 1/15),
                  (1/1e10, 1/1e10, 1/1e10),
                  (0.2, 0.5, 0.3)])
pars2 = np.array([(1/100, 1/40, 1/15),
                  (1/1e3, 1/1e4, 1/1e5),
                  (0.2, 0.5, 0.3)])

#build the SM kernels, both the full mixture and each 
#component separately for illustration
kernels1 = [ sm_kernel(x, *pars1) ] + \
           [ sm_kernel(x, *pars1[:,i]) for i in range(3) ]
kernels2 = [ sm_kernel(x, *pars2) ] + \
           [ sm_kernel(x, *pars2[:,i]) for i in range(3) ]
```

To facilitate using the SM kernel in a GP, I have coded the following helper class for building, training, sampling, and predicting.  Since the data (see the next section) are sampled at regular (hourly) intervals, I can represent the covariance matrix as a Toeplitz matrix and take advantage of efficient linear algebra operations.


```python
from numpy.linalg import cholesky
from scipy.linalg import solve_triangular, toeplitz, solve_toeplitz#, cho_solve, cho_factor
from scipy.optimize import differential_evolution

class SpectralMixtureGP_Toeplitz(object):
    def __init__(self, x, y, freq, var, weight, noise_var, store_sparse=True):
        self.store_sparse = store_sparse
        
        self.yi = y
        self.data_var = y.var()
        
        self.xi = x
        if self.store_sparse:
            self.col_dist = np.abs(x - x[0])
        else:
            self.col_dist = np.abs(x - x[:,None])
        self.nlog2pi = x.shape[0] * math.log(2*math.pi)
        
        self.pars = [np.atleast_1d(p) for p in (freq, var, weight, noise_var)]
        self.pars_array = np.hstack(self.pars)
        try:
            self.cr = self.build_cov()
        except:
            raise Exception("Failed to build the covariance matrix. "
                            "Try increasing the noise variance term.")
        
    def build_cov(self, *pars):
        """If provided, *pars takes four 1-D arrays as arguments, 
        such that: `_mean, _var, _weights, _noise = pars` is possible."""
        if len(pars) == 0:
            pars = self.pars
        
        if self.store_sparse:
            cov_row = sm_kernel(self.col_dist, *pars) * self.data_var
            return cov_row, cov_row
        else:
            return sm_kernel(self.col_dist, *pars) * self.data_var

    def expand_cov(self, cr=None):
        if cr is None:
            cr = self.cr
        
        if self.store_sparse:
            return toeplitz(*cr)
        else:
            return cr
    
    def logpdf(self, L=None):
        if L is None:
            L = np.linalg.cholesky( self.expand_cov() )
        
        #efficiently compute the log determinant and the squared exponential terms
        log_det = 2*np.log( np.diag(L) ).sum()
        z = solve_triangular(L, self.yi, lower=True)
        zdot = np.square(np.ascontiguousarray(z)).sum(axis=-1)
        
        return -0.5 * (self.nlog2pi + zdot + log_det)
    
    def _train(self, free_pars, idx):
        #merge the free parameters into the full parameter arrays
        pars = self.pars_array.copy()
        pars[idx] = free_pars
        gauss_mixture_pars = pars[:-1].reshape(3, len(pars)//3)
        
        #build and factorize the covariance matrix
        cr = self.build_cov(*gauss_mixture_pars, pars[-1:])
        L = np.linalg.cholesky( self.expand_cov(cr) )
        
        return -self.logpdf(L)

    def train(self, idx, init_pars=None, bounds=None, N_init=None, return_res=False, tol=3e-3):
        """this function allows one to fix/vary arbitrary parameter groups, but the
        free parameters passed in by `init_pars` and implied by `idx` need to be stacked
        in group order such that all the means come first, the variances second, weights
        third, and the noise parameter last.  Also, `idx` cannot be a slice object."""
        
        #count how many in each parameter group (m, v, w, n) get varied
        N = len(self.pars[0])
        bin_edges = np.append( np.arange(4)*N, [3*N+1] )
        counts, _ = np.histogram(idx, bin_edges)

        #estimate parameter bounds...this is very rough, supply targeted bounds
        #or see the `targeted_guess()` function defined in a later section
        if bounds is None:
            #assume uniform spacing over self.x
            delta_x = self.xi[1] - self.xi[0]
            
            #[(1e-12, 1/delta_x**2)] * counts[1] + \
            bounds = [(0, 1/delta_x)] * counts[0] + \
                     [(1e-12, 4e-6)] * (counts[1]-1) + \
                     [(1e-6, 1)] + \
                     [(0, 20)] * counts[2] + \
                     [(0, 1)] * counts[3]
        
        if N_init is None:
            N_init = len(bounds) * 2
        
        #use uniform sampling for initialization
        if init_pars is None:
            lo, hi = [*zip(*bounds)]
            init_pars = np.random.uniform(lo, hi, size=(N_init, len(lo)))
        elif init_pars.ndim == 1:
            if N_init == 1:
                init_pars = init_pars[None,:]
            else:
                random_factor = np.random.uniform(0.5, 1.5, size=(N_init, init_pars.size))
                init_pars = init_pars * random_factor
                init_pars = np.clip(init_pars, *zip(*bounds))
        #init_pars[..., noise_idx] /= self.data_var

        #I like this minimizer for finding global minima in complex functions without  
        #using gradients.  Note, I do not attempt to optimize its arguments here.
        res = differential_evolution(self._train, bounds=bounds, args=(idx,), 
                                     init=init_pars, tol=tol, polish=False)
        #an alternative minimizer routine
        # res = minimize(self._train, init_pars[0], bounds=bounds, args=(idx,))        
        
        #update self.pars to reflect the newly learned parameters
        self.pars_array[idx] = res.x
        self.pars = np.hsplit(self.pars_array[:-1], 3) + [self.pars_array[-1:]]
        self.cr = self.build_cov()
    
        if return_res:
            return res
    
    def predict(self, x, mu=0, cr=None, idx=None):
        if cr is None:
            cr = self.cr
        
        #setting idx will be useful for manually inspecting the
        #impact of individual kernel components on the prediction
        if idx is None:
            idx = slice(None)
                
        pars = [p[idx] for p in self.pars[:-1]]
        if self.store_sparse:
            #prep work...
            col_dist = np.abs(x-self.xi[0])
            row_dist = np.abs(self.xi-x[0])
            
            #build a matrix (similar to the cov matrix, but not square and w/o noise)
            cov_column = sm_kernel(col_dist, *pars) * self.data_var
            cov_row = sm_kernel(row_dist, *pars) * self.data_var
            rect_matrix = toeplitz(cov_column, cov_row)
            
            #efficiently solve the matrix equation C*coeffs = y, where C is the covariance 
            #matrix and coeffs is a vector
            coeffs = solve_toeplitz(cr, self.yi)
        else:
            pdist = np.abs(self.xi - x[:,None])
            rect_matrix = sm_kernel(pdist, *pars) * self.data_var
            
            #efficiently solve the matrix equation C*coeffs = y, where C is the covariance 
            #matrix and coeffs is a vector
            L = np.linalg.cholesky( self.expand_cov(cr) )
            tmp = solve_triangular(L, self.yi, lower=True)
            coeffs = solve_triangular(L.T, tmp, lower=False)

        return np.dot(rect_matrix, coeffs) + mu
    
    def sample(self, mu=0, size=1, L=None):
        if L is None:
            L = np.linalg.cholesky( self.expand_cov() )

        if isinstance(size, int):
            size = (size,)
        
        #generate random samples from the standard (univariate) normal distribution
        u = np.random.normal(size=size + self.xi.shape)   #tuple concatenation
        
        #get multivariate normal samples via inner product with the cholesky factor
        rvs = np.dot(u,self.L.T)
        
        return mu + rvs


```

## Rhode Island Historical Load and Weather Data

Many factors determine the load on the electric power system at any given moment.  Climate variables such as temperature, humidity, wind, cloud cover and precipitation impact the grid stochastically on short timescales.  Meanwhile, societal factors, as well as long term weather patterns, tend to be more cyclical in nature with daily, weekly, annual, and seasonal patterns.  Some aperiodic societal factors also influence the load such as population growth, technological advances, and political regulations, but their effects are generally felt on longer timescales.

Since both climate and societal factors vary geographically, it is important to select historical load and weather data properly weighted to represent the same region.  Rhode Island is a small state near the Eastern seaboard, so the average load and average weather should align with each other better than in any of the other New England states.  In contrast, Massachusetts, which has a strong rising population density moving from West to East, is an example of where geographically-weighted average weather reports would be misaligned with the (population-weighted) average load.

For the electric load, I pulled [historical demand](https://www.iso-ne.com/isoexpress/web/reports/load-and-demand/-/tree/demand-by-zone) data from [ISO New England](https://www.iso-ne.com)'s website.  ISO New England is an Independent System Operator, one of seven across the continental U.S., which means it is an independent (not-for-profit) third party designated by law to operate the electricity markets and oversee electric power distribution, including day to day operations as well as long term planning.  They only make their data accessible in 45 day batches.  I targeted two years of data (I ended up with 2/14/18 to 3/13/20, i.e., 25 months), so it was more efficient to manually concatenate the individual files rather than automate the procedure.

Loading the data into a Pandas DataFrame and setting up the datetime variable looks like this...with the two columns giving the amount of electric energy (measured in megawatt-hours) and the date/hour it was needed.

For weather data, the [Iowa Environmental Mesonet (IEM)](https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu) archives hourly [airport weather reports](https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/request/download.phtml) from around the world.  I have no reason to prefer the IEM over other sources, other than that it is the first publicly available collection of the sort that I could find online.  I downloaded weather data from the same time period as the electric load data including air temperature, precipitation, and cloud cover records.  I only ended up using the air temperature in this project, though in a more thorough undertaking I would certainly investigate incorporating additional variables (including ones I did not download, such as humidity and wind speed).

Below I load the weather data into a Pandas DataFrame in a similar manner as I did with the electric load data.  The `temp`, `precip01mm`, and `cloud` columns respectively refer to the ambient temperature, the recorded level of precipitation (in millimeters), and a simple cloudiness index I derived from the cloud cover codes.  The cloudiness index ranges from zero for clear skies to one for overcast or rainy skies.


```python
def set_tz(x):
    date = pd.to_datetime(x).dt.ceil('h')
    return date.dt.tz_localize('America/New_York', ambiguous='infer')

weather_datafile = "/Users/kaiser/pythonapps/electric_load_3day_forecast/RI_2yr_weather.csv"
wthr_df = pd.read_csv(weather_datafile)

#adjust the `date` column for daylight savings time
wthr_df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(wthr_df.groupby('station')['date'].apply(set_tz))

#define a simple "cloudiness index", where 0=no clouds, 4=overcast
sky_cols = ['skyc1', 'skyc2', 'skyc3']
wthr_df['cloud'] = wthr_df[sky_cols].replace({'CLR': 0, 'FEW': 0.25, 'SCT': 0.5,
                                      'BKN': 0.75, 'OVC': 1, 'VV ': 1}).agg('max', axis=1)
cloudy = wthr_df.groupby('date', as_index=False)['cloud'].mean()

#take the mean of all measurements per hour
wthr_df = wthr_df.groupby('date', as_index=False)[['temp', 'precip01mm']].mean()
wthr_df['cloud'] = cloudy['cloud']

print(wthr_df)
```

## Spectral Density Analysis

The SM kernel is particularly well-suited for data with some underlying periodicity due to its cosine term (or the Gaussian location parameter in Fourier/frequency space).  Both the weather (especially the ambient temperature) and the electric power demand exhibit strongly periodic patterns with time.  Annual and daily cycles are present in both, while the load also fluctuates on at least a weekly timescale.  These patterns, and their relative intensities, show up nicely in the power spectral density (PSD) of the two data types, which I've illustrated below for the electric load data.  The authors of the SM kernel paper ([Wilson & Adams (2013)](http://proceedings.mlr.press/v28/wilson13.html)) point out a close relationship between the SM kernel and its spectral density.  In fact, one way of building an SM kernel is by fitting a Gaussian mixture model to the PSD, which I will demonstrate below.

A power spectrum is simply the squared Fourier transform of a time series data, with peaks at the most important frequencies.  Perfect spikes (i.e., dirac delta functions with no width) in a PSD indicate simple sinusoid periodicity in the data (in the time domain).  Broader, (e.g., Gaussian-shaped) spikes in frequency space dampen the amplitude of the periodic behavior in the time domain, with the length scale of the damping function inversely proportional to the width of the peak.  The x-axis location of the peak in Fourier space represents the frequency of the signal, which is also inversely proportional to the period in the time domain.

All of this is much clearer with an actual example.  Below, I plot the estimated PSD (and a zoom-in) for the electric load data.  There are significant spikes at 12, 24, and 168 hours as expected, but somewhat unexpectedly, the long-term patterns include periodic components that repeat at 1, 1/2, and 1/3 year intervals.  This does not necessarily mean that there is a dominant four month pattern, for example, (though that is possible), but that a four month pattern coupled with a six-month and a 12-month pattern reproduces the observed long-term trends.



```python
from scipy.signal import periodogram, find_peaks

#plot the power spectral density (PSD)
def plot_psd(y, min_peak, distance=1, plot=True, **fig_kwargs):
    #this estimates the power spectral density and selects the strongest peaks
    freq, density = periodogram(y)
    #want to set `min_peak` to select only peaks that stick out above the noise
    pidx, _ = find_peaks(density, height=min_peak*density.max(), distance=distance)
    
    if plot:
        plt.figure(**fig_kwargs)
        plt.plot(freq, density)
        plt.plot(freq[pidx], density[pidx], 'o')
        plt.xlabel('Frequency [hour$^-1$]')
        plt.ylabel('Estimated Power Spectral Density')
    
    return freq, density, pidx

#plot the full PSD
freq, density, pidx = plot_psd(df['load'], 0.04, figsize=(6,3))
plt.subplots_adjust(bottom=0.2)

#zoom-in on the shortest frequencies (the longest periods)
freq, density, pidx = plot_psd(df['load'], 0.04, figsize=(6,3))
plt.subplots_adjust(bottom=0.2)
plt.xlim([0, 0.001])
plt.ylim([0, 1.5e8])

```

While the limited range and sampling of the electric load dataset (i.e., it includes just over two years of hourly data) obscures the shape of these peaks, I can fit the PSD with a Gaussian mixture model to estimate their widths and more precisely measure their peak frequencies.  I want to use a Gaussian mixture model because the inferred component Gaussians are just what I need to build an SM kernel.

Note: I wrote the Gaussian mixture model fitting function `gmm_density` below to take the output from `plot_psd` as its input.  The `plot_psd` function takes an argument controlling the number of peaks.  `gmm_density` fits a separate Gaussian for each peak, so selecting a large number of peaks may slow the minimization step in `gmm_density`.


```python
from scipy.optimize import minimize
from scipy.stats import expon

#builds a Gaussian mixture density with means, standard deviations, and weights = m, s, w
def multi_gauss(x, m, s, w):
    f = w * np.exp(-0.5 * ((x[:,None] - m)/s)**2)
    return np.sum(f, axis=-1)

#I chose to minimize the RMS error (versus some other statistic) for simplicity
def rms(pars, x, y):
    N = len(pars)//3
    m, s, w = pars.reshape(3, N)
    f = multi_gauss(x, m, s, w)
    _rms = np.sqrt( np.mean((y - f)**2) )
    return _rms

#estimates initial parameters and boundary conditions based on the spectral density
def targeted_guess(x, y, peak_indicies, append_extra=[], var_factor=10, 
                   var_as_sigma=False):
    delta_x = x[1] - x[0]
    delta_x_v = delta_x if var_as_sigma else delta_x**2
    
    #guess some reasonable initial parameters
    init_m = x[peak_indicies]
    init_v = np.zeros_like(init_m) + delta_x_v / 4
    init_w = y[peak_indicies] / y.sum()
    if append_extra:   #if extra is not empty
        extra_m, extra_v, extra_w = [*zip(*append_extra)]
        init_m = np.append(extra_m, init_m)
        init_v = np.append(extra_v, init_v)
        init_w = np.append(extra_w, init_w)
    
    #estimate parameter bounds
    bounds = targeted_bounds(x, init_m, init_v, init_w, var_factor)
    return np.hstack((init_m, init_v, init_w)), bounds
    
def targeted_bounds(x, init_m, init_v, init_w, var_factor=10, A_factor=1):
    #set reasonable parameter bounds for the minimizer...
    N = len(init_m)
    delta_x = x[1] - x[0]
    mu_lo = np.maximum(0, init_m - delta_x)
    mu_hi = np.minimum(x[-1], init_m + delta_x)
    mu_bnds = [*zip(mu_lo, mu_hi)]
    
    var_bnds = [*zip(init_v/var_factor, init_v*var_factor)]
#     var_bnds = [(0, delta_x_v * var_factor)] * N
    
    A_lo = np.maximum(0, init_w-0.25*A_factor)
    A_hi = np.minimum(A_factor, init_w+0.25*A_factor)
    A_bnds = [*zip(A_lo, A_hi)]
#     A_bnds = [(0, A_factor)] * N
    
    return mu_bnds + var_bnds + A_bnds   #list concatenation

#fits a Gaussian mixture model to the spectral density
def gmm_density(x, y, init_arg, initializer=targeted_guess, **kwargs):
    #estimate the initial parameters and bounds
    extra = kwargs.pop('append_extra', [])
    initpars, bounds = initializer(x, y, init_arg, var_as_sigma=True, 
                                   append_extra=extra)
    
    #minimize the RMS error...`result` is a scipy.optimize.OptimizeResult object
    y_normed = y / y.sum()
    result = minimize(rms, initpars, args=(x, y_normed), bounds=bounds)
    
    #convert standard deviations to variances
    out = result.x.reshape(3, len(initpars)//3)
    out[1] *= out[1]

    #shape of out is such that m, v, w = gmm_density(...)
    return out
```


```python
#fit the Gaussian mixture model to the PSD
gm_pars = gmm_density(freq, density, pidx)
```

## Pattern Discovery with the SM Kernel

To recap, I just identified the dominant frequencies in the 2yr electric load data and fit each one with a Gaussian model.  Now, how do I incorporate this information into a Gaussian process model?  This is where the SM kernel shines.  All I have to do is invert (take the reciprocal of) the Gaussian means and variances and collect the mixture weights and I have everything needed to specify an SM kernel.

The code below tries this out...


```python
#flexible plotting helper for comparing observed and predicted data
def plot_GP_pred(true_data, pred_data=None, zoom_index=None, 
                 labels=('True load', 'GP model'), axes=None):
    if axes is None:
        fig, axes = plt.subplots( nrows=(1 if zoom_index is None else 2) )
        fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.35, bottom=0.2, top=0.95)
        pd.plotting.register_matplotlib_converters()

    for i, axis in enumerate(np.atleast_1d(axes)):
        slc = zoom_index if i==1 else slice(None)
        axis.plot(true_data[0][slc], true_data[1][slc], label=labels[0])
        if pred_data is not None:
            axis.plot(pred_data[0][slc], pred_data[1][slc], label=labels[1])
        axis.legend(loc='upper center')
        plt.setp(axis.get_xticklabels(), rotation=30, ha='right')
    
    return axes

#define a convenience function for selecting date ranges
def slice_by_date(start_date_str, end_date_str, df=df):
    """Assumes `df` contains hourly samples.  The selected range will not  
    include the end date.  If `start_date_str` can be interpreted as a integer
    index than a Python s`lice(start, stop)` object will be returned."""
    if (start_date_str is None) or isinstance(start_date_str, int):
        return slice(start_date_str, end_date_str)
    
    RI_tz = 'America/New_York'
    start_date = pd.to_datetime(start_date_str).tz_localize(RI_tz)
    end_date = pd.to_datetime(end_date_str).tz_localize(RI_tz)
    mask = (df['date'] >= start_date) & (df['date'] < end_date)
    return np.nonzero(mask.values)[0]

#initialize a GP process with an SM kernel
x_in, y_in = df.index.values, df['load']
noise_frac = 0.5   #estimates the noise as a fraction of the variance of `y_in`
SMGP = SpectralMixtureGP_Toeplitz(x_in, y_in-y_in.mean(), *gm_pars, noise_frac)

#compare the GP predicted `y_out` values to the `y_in`
#data at the same input coordinates `x_in`
y_out = SMGP.predict(x_in, mu=y_in.mean())
#zoom_slc = slice_by_date('2019-08-18', '2019-09-08')
zoom_slc = slice_by_date('2019-01-18', '2019-02-08')
axes = plot_GP_pred((df['date'], y_in), (df['date'], y_out), zoom_index=zoom_slc)
axes[1].set_xlabel('Date')

```

Okay, that attempt seems to capture some of the long-term structure in the data, but otherwise it fails rather badly.  What went wrong?  Well, two things.  First, I derived the kernel parameters from the PSD, which, by design, only reveals periodic features.  This is a problem, because a periodic-only kernel cannot replicate stochastic variations in the data, and because it tries to anyway and ends up distorting the inferred periodic structures.  One way to mitigate this issue is by shortening the length scales of the kernel components; doing so leads to locally periodic behavior.  The second issue, however, is that the Gaussian mixture components inferred from fitting to the load's PSD all have short widths, which translates to long length scales.  Longer is better for prediction, since short length scales quickly "forget" previous patterns in the (historical) data.  However, long length scales also are harder to fit, since they are less flexible.

An easy way to address these shortcomings is to simply add a single aperiodic component to the SM kernel.  Setting the period of this component to infinity assures it is aperiodic.  Giving it a short length scale allows it to essentially fill in the cracks left by the periodic part of the SM kernel.  The figure below shows how much this extra kernel component improves the model.  

Indeed, one particularly exciting aspect of combining an SM kernel with a Gaussian Process is how easy it is to decompose the data into stochastic and periodic components.  The figure below also illustrates the various patterns inferred from this revised model of the electric load dataset.


```python
#append an aperiodic component to the SM kernel
gm_pars_plus1 = []
gm_pars_plus1 += [np.append(gm_pars[0], 1/np.inf)]   #infinite period = aperiodic
gm_pars_plus1 += [np.append(gm_pars[1], 1/1)]   #a short 1-hour length scale
gm_pars_plus1 += [np.append(gm_pars[2], 1)]   #the weight doesn't need to be precise

#overwrite the old GP process with the updated SM kernel
y_in_mu = y_in.mean()
SMGP = SpectralMixtureGP_Toeplitz(x_in, y_in-y_in_mu, *gm_pars_plus1, 1e-2)
y_out = SMGP.predict(x_in, mu=y_in_mu)

#reproduce the previous comparison plot, but with a (hopefully!) better prediction
fig, ax = plt.subplots(3, 1, figsize=(8, 7))
fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.45, bottom=0.15, top=0.95)

#extract and plot some of the inferred periodic components of the data
y_seasonal = SMGP.predict(x_in, mu=y_in_mu, idx=slice(0,3))   #sums the 1, 1/2, and 1/3 year patterns
y_weekly = SMGP.predict(x_in, idx=slice(3,4))   #selects the weekly patterns
y_daily = SMGP.predict(x_in, idx=slice(4,7))   #sums the 12 and 24 hour patterns
y_random = SMGP.predict(x_in, idx=slice(-1,None))   #selects the (primarily) stochastic variations
y_periodic = y_seasonal + y_weekly + y_daily

#slc = slice_by_date('2019-08-18', '2019-09-08')
slc = slice_by_date('2019-01-18', '2019-02-08')
axes = plot_GP_pred((df['date'], y_in), (df['date'], y_out), zoom_index=slc, axes=ax[:2])
axes[0].plot(df['date'], y_seasonal, label='Seasonal pattern')

ax[2].plot(df['date'][slc], y_random[slc], color='black', label='Aperiodic fluctuations')
ax[2].plot(df['date'][slc], y_daily[slc], label='Daily pattern')
ax[2].plot(df['date'][slc], y_weekly[slc], label='Weekly pattern')
plt.setp(ax[2].get_xticklabels(), rotation=30, ha='right')
ax[2].legend(loc='upper center', ncol=2)
ax[2].set_ylim([None, 480])
ax[2].set_xlabel('Date')
```

This revised model greatly improves the fit over the purely periodic model, yet it still leaves ample room for improvement.  In particular, although this model can be made arbitrarily accurate (by reducing the noise scale of the load data) with respect to the training data, the aperiodic component of the model has a very short timescale and as a result, essentially no predictive power.  Thus, to get a sense of the *minimum* noise uncertainty one might expect from a prediction using this model, I computed the root mean square (RMS) and standard deviation of the periodic-only residual (i.e., the historical load minus the periodic components of the GP model).  The statistics are printed below.  Alternatively, one simply has to look at the bottom panel of the figure above to see that the variance in the aperiodic components is comparable to that of the periodic ones.  Ideally, it should be much less.


```python
#define a utility function to print some basic goodness of fit statistics
def report_error(y_test, y_true, header=''):
    prcnt_error = (np.abs(y_test - y_true) / y_true) * 100
    gauss_error = np.std( (y_test - y_true) / y_true ) * 100
    rms_error = np.sqrt(np.mean(prcnt_error**2))

    print('\n' + header)
    print("The (Gaussian) standard deviation in the percent error is {:.1f}%".format(gauss_error))
    print("The RMS percent error is {:.1f}%".format(rms_error))
    print("The average hourly percent error is {:.1f}%".format(prcnt_error.mean()))
    print("The max percent error is {:.1f}".format(prcnt_error.max()))

y_periodic = y_out - y_random
report_error(y_periodic, df.load, '---25 month model fit---')
```

## Electric Load Forecasting

In the previous section I showed how one can isolate patterns in the data using a Gaussian process.  Now I will focus on refining the Gaussian process to make it useful for prediction.  The predictive power of the SM kernel comes from its periodic components, so any refinements should be aimed at minimizing the stochastic (non-periodic) component.  How can I do this?  There are several possibilities.  
1. I might try adjusting the existing kernel parameters to optimize the fit.  This is commonly referred to as *training* the model, and it is too computationally expensive to do over the full two year period, though perhaps a shorter period would suffice?


2. I might take the stochastic residual and analyze and model it separately in the hope of finding some periodic/long duration patterns that did not get picked up by the periodic components I specified for the full model.


3. I could try using extra information (e.g., historical weather data) to model the aperiodic fluctations in the load.  This approach makes a lot of sense, but weather modeling/forecasting is a whole separate problem that likely requires more than a single Gaussian Process kernel.

Below, I will explore all three of these options to some degree, though for the third, I will not attempt to forecast the weather since stationary Gaussian processes are likely ill-suited for short-term weather prediction.

### Training the GP hyperparameters

The parameters of the SM kernel components are *hyperparameters* of the Gaussian process model.  Using the vocabulary of machine learning, I want to *learn* these hyperparameters by training the Gaussian process on some subset of the data, called the *training set*.  The goal is to find parameters that optimize the model with respect to the training data in the hope that these parameters will also provide good predictive power.

This sounds great in principle, though in practice it often becomes a difficult optimization problem, particularly if the kernel requires several narrow mixture components like those indicated by the PSD above.  After tinkering with several options for initializing parameters and boundary conditions for the optimizer, I discovered that the boundary condition on the kernel component variances is crucial.  With a lax upper limit, the GP turns several strongly periodic components (as indicated by the PSD) into quasi-/locally periodic ones.  This creates marginally better models over the training data, but ones that are highly variable over the test data.  To tamp this effect down, I reduced the variances by a factor of ten and tightly restricted their upper limit to a factor of two above the initial guess.

The three code blocks immediately below select some portion of the load dataset to use as training data, build a GP, train it, make predictions, and report some basic statistics about the accuracy of the 24-hour and 3-day predictions.  The subsequent (fourth) code block plots the GP for visual comparison with the historical load data.  Actually, rather than wasting the model derived above, I subtracted the seasonal and weekly periodic components of the prior model from the historical data before modeling again.  This step actually improves the model even more than the training step, which is an interesting observation I exploit in the next section.


```python
#set up the training and testing data...
normalized_load = df['load'] - y_seasonal - y_weekly
train_slc = slice_by_date('2019-01-03', '2019-02-06')
full_slc = slice_by_date('2019-01-03', '2019-02-13')
# train_slc = slice_by_date('2019-12-01', '2020-01-12')
# full_slc = slice_by_date('2019-12-01', '2020-01-19')
test_slc24 = slice(-168, -168+24)   #to be used on objects already sliced by full_slc
test_slc72 = slice(-168, -168+72)   #to be used on objects already sliced by full_slc
x_train = df.index.values[train_slc]
y_train = normalized_load[train_slc]
x_true = df.index.values[full_slc]
y_true = normalized_load[full_slc]

#get the periodic kernel components by fitting the PSD
psd_pars2 = plot_psd(y_train, 0.015, plot=False)
gm_pars2 = gmm_density(*psd_pars2)
gm_pars2[1] /= 10   #divide the kernel component variances forcing them to be more periodic

#add an aperiodic kernel component
gm_pars2_plus1 = []
for i in range(3):
    gm_pars2_plus1 += [np.append( (1/np.inf, 1/0.5, 1)[i], gm_pars2[i] )]

#build the GP
noise_factor = 0.1   #gets multiplied by `y_train.var()`
SMGP2 = SpectralMixtureGP_Toeplitz(x_train, y_train-y_train.mean(), 
                                   *gm_pars2_plus1, noise_factor)
```


```python

free_pars_indices = [i for i in range(1, SMGP2.pars_array.size)]
initp = SMGP2.pars_array[free_pars_indices]
bounds = ([*zip(SMGP2.pars[0]/2, SMGP2.pars[0]*2)] +    #kernel component means
          [*zip(SMGP2.pars[1]/1000, SMGP2.pars[1]*2)] +  #kernel component variances
          [*zip(SMGP2.pars[2]/10, SMGP2.pars[2]*3)] +    #kernel component weights
          [(2e-2, 1)])                                  #data noise factor

fitted_pars_object = SMGP2.train(free_pars_indices, init_pars=initp, bounds=bounds,
                                 N_init=initp.shape[-1]*2, return_res=True, tol=3e-3)
```

The shaded parts of the figure above indicate regions where the blue data was only used for prediction, (i.e., not as part of the training set).

Even with the initialization adjustments discussed above, this model generally fails to fall within 5% or 6% of the true data.  (I tested this for several different slices of training data.)  It does, however, represent an improvement over the minimum 9% errors expected without training the GP parameters.  The stochastic component still plays an outsized role in the model, so there is plenty of room for improvement by better or deeper modeling of that component as I noted above.

Additionally, I identified several potential improvements to the model training methodology that I will not explore further here.  These include:
1. Including the number of kernel mixture components in the optimization.  The objective function is a Bayesian probability (of the hyperparameters given the training), so it naturally resists overfitting making it a reasonable strategy to fold the number of components into the objective.


2. Exploring the optimal length of a training set.  Essentially, how much data is needed to make a good (the best) prediction?  Oddly, too much data *can* be counter productive, though too little is even worse.
  * Additionally, one could compare predictions from GPs trained at different length scales to get a sense how uncertain the predictions are.


3. Using a different objective function.  In particular, I suspect it would be useful train the GP to optimally predict (interpolate) random 1 week chunks of load data that are taken from the training set for this purpose.  This would still be possible to accomplish with efficient Toeplitz matrices, though it would require significantly rewriting the code given above to do so.


### Refining the model

As I briefly mentioned above, re-modeling the data after removing some or all of its periodic components can actually improve the prediction without doing anything else.  Clearly there is some periodic component in the data that my PSD fitting approach misses.  What if I simply repeat this procedure multiple times, each time estimating a PSD of the previous model's residual and building a kernel and (GP) modeling it separately?  In fact, this approach does quite well, in some cases pushing the RMS uncertainty down below 3%-4% (especially in the winter where the stochasticity induced by the weather is minimal).  This iterative or layered approach is particularly exciting because it is fast and does not require training the model (though training is possible).

The following box of code does two things: 1) it consolidates the kernel estimation and GP building/training/predicting procedures discussed above into a single, optionally recursive function, and 2) it builds a `DataSlice` class to provide a cleaner interface for selecting training and testing datasets.  The `DataSlice` class also makes it select random regions of the dataset, which is important for gauging how effective the prediction throughout the year.



```python
def iterative_gp(x_train, y_train, x_pred, y_pred=0, Niter=1, init_psd=None,
                 min_psd=0.2, max_cmpnts=10, min_dist=1, train=True):
    #set up the kernel components by fitting the PSD and adding an aperiodic component
    if init_psd is None:
        freq, density, pidx = plot_psd(y_train, min_psd, distance=min_dist, plot=False)
        pidx = pidx[ np.argsort(density[pidx])[:-max_cmpnts-1:-1] ]
        gm_pars = gmm_density(freq, density, pidx)
    else:
        gm_pars = gmm_density(*init_psd)
    pars_plus1 = [np.append( (1/np.inf, 1/0.5**2, 0.5)[i], gm_pars[i] ) for i in range(3)]

    #build and train the GP, using the fitted PSD parameters as initial parameters
    SMGP = SpectralMixtureGP_Toeplitz(x_train, y_train-y_train.mean(), *pars_plus1, 1e-0)
    if train:
        free_idx = [i for i in range(1, SMGP.pars_array.size)]
        initp = SMGP.pars_array[free_idx]
        bounds = ([*zip(SMGP.pars[0]/2, SMGP.pars[0]*2)] + 
                  [*zip(SMGP.pars[1]/1000, SMGP.pars[1]*2)] + 
                  [*zip(SMGP.pars[2]/10, SMGP.pars[2]*3)] + [(2e-2, 1)])
        bounds = [bounds[i] for i in free_idx]
        _ = SMGP.train(free_idx, init_pars=initp, bounds=bounds, N_init=initp.shape[-1]*2)

    y_pred += SMGP.predict(x_pred, mu=y_train.mean(), idx=slice(1,None))

    if Niter > 1:
        periodic = SMGP.predict(x_train, mu=y_train.mean(), idx=slice(1,None))
        residual = y_train - periodic
        return iterative_gp(x_train, residual, x_pred, y_pred, Niter-1, None, 
                            min_psd, max_cmpnts, min_dist, train)
    else:
        aperiodic = SMGP.predict(x_pred, idx=slice(0,1))
        return y_pred + aperiodic, SMGP


class DataSlice(object):
    def __init__(self, df, load=None, start=None, num_hours=45*24, random_state=None):
        load = df['load'] if load is None else load
        if start is None:
            if random_state is not None:
                np.random.set_state(random_state)
                print("setting random state!")
            start = np.random.choice(len(df) - num_hours) +18*24
        elif isinstance(start, str):
            try:
                start_date = pd.to_datetime(start).tz_localize('America/New_York')
                start = df[df['date'] == start_date].index
            except:
                msg = 'The string "{}" could not be interpreted as a date'.format(start)
                raise ValueError(msg)
        self.state = np.random.get_state()
        self.start = start
        
        self.full_slc = slice(start, start + num_hours)
        self.train_slc = slice(start, start + num_hours - 168)
        self.test_slc = slice(-168, None)
        self.test_slc3 = slice(-168, -168+72)
        self.test_slc24 = slice(-168, -168+24)
        
        self.dates = df['date'][self.full_slc]
        self.dates_train = df['date'][self.train_slc]
        self.x = df.index.values[self.full_slc]
        self.x_train = df.index.values[self.train_slc]
        self.y = load[self.full_slc]
        self.y_train = load[self.train_slc]
        self.y_train_mu = self.y_train.mean()

```

So, now that I have the tools I need, I will go ahead and model a random selection of dates, using 4 weeks of training data and predicting ahead 24-72 hours.  Actually, I use more than four weeks of training data, because I incorporate the seasonal, weekly, and daily trends inferred over the full dataset above.  Every time you run the block of code below it will produce a new set of predictions at randomly selected times.  

In most cases, this model performs significantly better than previous ones, at least for prediction.  In lieu of a more thorough investigation, it appears that the poorest predictions primarily occur during the summer or close to a holiday (which typically produce major dips in the load).  During the winter in particular, the 24-hour predictions frequently fall below a 3-4% RMS percent error.



```python
normalized_load = df['load'] - y_seasonal - y_weekly - y_daily

for i in range(10):
    D = DataSlice(df, load=normalized_load, start=None, num_hours=35*24)
    y_pred, SMGP = iterative_gp(D.x_train, D.y_train - D.y_train_mu, D.x, D.y_train_mu,
                                Niter=25, min_psd=0.5, max_cmpnts=3, min_dist=1, train=False)

    residual = D.y - y_pred
    pm_prcnt_error = (residual / df['load'][D.full_slc]) * 100
    rms_error24 = np.sqrt(np.mean(pm_prcnt_error[test_slc24]**2))
    rms_error72 = np.sqrt(np.mean(pm_prcnt_error[test_slc72]**2))

    start_date = D.dates[test_slc72][:1].dt.strftime("%Y-%m-%d").values[0]
    print("\n---Statistics for the prediction beginning at date {}".format(start_date))
    print("The 24-hour RMS percent error is  {:.1f}%".format(rms_error24))
    print("The 3-day RMS percent error is    {:.1f}%".format(rms_error72))
```

### Incorporating Temperature Data into the Electric Load Forecast

The layered GP approach I showcased in the preceeding section performs far better than a single GP, while retaining the same interpretability of the single GP.  Still, this approach suffers from inconsistent predictions.  As I have noted previously, this is primarily due to the stochastic component of the data.  I suspect that the stochasticity owes predominantly to the influence of the weather.  In particular, the ambient temperature is a major driver of energy consumption and variability, whether for heating in the winter or cooling in the summer.

I would guess that the best way to use Gaussian processes to enhance prediction accuracy by incorporating weather variables would probably be to model those variables alongside the load in a *multi-output* Gaussian process.  The term "multi-output" essentially means that in addition to the covariances in each variable along the time dimension, there are also cross-covariances between variables (e.g., between the temperature and load).  This approach is not trivial to implement, however, and would require another Jupyter notebook to introduce.  Since my goal here is merely to illustrate the close relation between Rhode Island's historical temperature data and the stochastic component of the load data, I will instead limit myself to briefly highlighting the relation between these two variables.

To illustrate how tightly the temperature and load correlate, I compared their (what I am calling) "stochastic residuals" in the following plot.  By stochastic residuals, I mean the remaining stochastic component of the two datasets after subtracting any periodic components (which I ascertain using SM kernel-based GPs).  


```python
from scipy.ndimage import gaussian_filter1d

def divide_std(x):
    return x / x.std()

#estimate the periodic portion of the temperature data...
#...set plot=True to see the PSD
T_pars = gmm_density( *plot_psd(df['temp'], 0.05, plot=False) )
T_pars_plus1 = [np.append( (1/np.inf, 1/0.5**2, 0.5)[i], T_pars[i] ) for i in range(3)]
T_avg = df['temp'].mean()
SMGP_T = SpectralMixtureGP_Toeplitz(df.index.values, df['temp'] - T_avg, *T_pars_plus1, 1)
T_seasonal = SMGP_T.predict(df.index.values, mu=T_avg, idx=slice(1, None))


#compute and smooth the "stochastic residuals"
load_rnd = df.load - y_seasonal - y_weekly - y_daily
load_rnd_smooth = gaussian_filter1d(load_rnd, 18)
temp_rnd = df.temp.values - T_seasonal
temp_rnd_smooth = gaussian_filter1d(temp_rnd, 18)

#prep seasonal data slices
summer_slc = slice_by_date("2018-04-15", "2018-10-15")
winter_slc = slice_by_date("2018-10-15", "2019-04-15")
seasonal_indices = (summer_slc, winter_slc)

#plot the smoothed residuals
fig, axarr = plt.subplots(2, 1)
fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.6, bottom=0.15)
labels = ('Load residual', 'Temperature residual')
for i, (ax, idx) in enumerate(zip(axarr, seasonal_indices)):
    ax.plot(df.date[idx], divide_std(load_rnd_smooth[idx]), label=labels[0])
    ax.plot(df.date[idx], divide_std(temp_rnd_smooth[idx]), label=labels[1])
    plt.setp(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=30, ha='right')
axarr[0].set_ylim([None, 4.5])
axarr[0].legend(loc='upper left')
axarr[0].set_title('Summer 2018')
axarr[1].set_title('Winter 2018/19')
axarr[1].set_xlabel('Date')

```

In addition to a stark correlation between the two datasets in the summer, I also observe a strong anti-correlation in the winter and a bi-annual amplitude variation in the load residual.  The anti-correlation makes sense because in the winter, colder than average temperatures require more energy for heating, while in the summer, hotter than average temperatures require more energy for cooling.  The load amplitude is greater in the summer and winter than in the spring and fall because the first two seasons experience more extreme temperatures, hence demanding more extreme energy totals.


## Conclusions

Back at the beginning of this notebook, I stated that my primary intention was to analyze and decompose patterns in the data using an SM kernel.  So, how did that work out?  Well, I showed how one can model the information in the power spectral density of a dataset to build a kernel out of a mixture of Gaussians in Fourier space.  Indeed, the PSD does practically all the hard work for us and leaves little need to further train the kernel hyperparameters.

I also demonstrated that it is possible to decompose kernels into the periodic or aperiodic components represented by each kernel mixture component.  This incredible capability of a simple Gaussian process model in tandem with a spectral mixture kernel is what really sets this tool apart from other machine learning techniques.  The periodic patterns I uncovered offer a meaningful baseline for assessing day-to-day or year-to-year variations.  Without a robust baseline, it can be difficult to measure the effect a certain holiday, for example, might have on the demand for electric power.

An even more interesting application, in my opinion, is the potential for really understanding how the load depends on weather variables.  I only scratched the surface by comparing the tightly correlated temperature and load "stochastic residuals," but as I suggested above, a multi-dimensional Gaussian process could offer much richer insights into these load-weather relationships.

The ultimate goal, of course, is accurate, reliable forecasting.  Using a layered or nested GP approach, I managed to bring down the RMS percent error in the 24-hour forecast during much of the winter months to within 3-4% without any additional information.  This is quite impressive for a single-GP model!  More successful (at prediction) GP approaches often rely on a mixture of GPs (e.g., analogous to a Gaussian mixture model).  While the forecasts shown here are certainly not consistent enough to be reliable, I highlighted several steps that could be explored to improve the predictive accuracy, ranging from improved training techniques to incorporating additional weather data (not just temperature).  Perhaps, one day when I have more time, I might try building that multi-dimensional GP model I keep mentioning.
